Background

We have explored how various U.S. economic indicators are related to each other, which is a classic application for the VAR modeling. In this problem, we will study the inter-dependence and Granger causality between various economic indicators.

Instructions on reading the data

To read the data in R, save the file in your working directory (make sure you have changed the directory if different from the R working directory) and read the data using the R function read.csv()

Plot the time series of all indicators for comparison and discuss whether you find any similarities in terms of trend or other features. Plot also the 1st order difference plots and the corresponding ACF plots. Interpret in terms of stationarity and volatility.

Keep in mind, 2 variables have monthly data, while three have quarterly data. You will need to standardise all into quarterly data time series in order to effectively answer all questions below.

Response

Comparing the time series plots, the gdp, export, import as well as PCE all move in the same trend in general. This proves to be consistent to traditional economic theory that trade and consumption drives the GDP up. The unemployment rate does not show a clear trend but does show some level of seasonality. The acf plots show nonstationarity for all the factors, which can also be reflected in the differenced time series plots, where the difference gets larger between 2000 and 2010. The ACF of the differenced data also show good stationality.

test_model <- function(data,p,q){
    mod = arima(data, order=c(p,0,q), method="ML")
    current.aic <- AIC(mod)
    current.aic<-current.aic-2*(p+q+1)+2*(p+q+1)*length(data)/(length(data)-p-q-2)
    df = data.frame(p,q,current.aic)
    names(df) <- c("p","q","AIC")
    #print(paste(p,q,current.aic,sep=" "))
    return(df)
}

gdp_orders <- data.frame(Inf,Inf,Inf)
names(gdp_orders) <- c("p","q","AIC")
for (p in 0:6){
    for (q in 0:6) {
        possibleError <- tryCatch(
            gdp_orders<-rbind(gdp_orders,test_model(train_gdp,p,q)),
            error=function(e) e
        )
        if(inherits(possibleError, "error")) next
    }
}

Response

The prediction fails to predict the downward trend and thus significantly deviates from the observed data. This is because the p value, ie the autogressive term in the arima model is 4 lags so the results are highly dependent on the previous data points. Given that previously their is obvious increasing trend in gdp and thus the prediction is heavily influenced by this bias.

test_model <- function(data,p,d,q){
    mod = arima(data, order=c(p,d,q), method="ML")
    current.aic <- AIC(mod)
    current.aic<-current.aic-2*(p+q+1)+2*(p+q+1)*length(data)/(length(data)-p-q-2)
    df = data.frame(p,d,q,current.aic)
    names(df) <- c("p","d","q","AIC")
    #print(paste(p,q,current.aic,sep=" "))
    return(df)
}

# Estimated coefficients and their variance for Bitcoin regression Equation

n = 5 # there are 3 different regressors 
p = 20 # our var selected order

var.all = vcov(mod_aic_3)

## coefficient and variance-covariance matrix for gdp
coef.gdp = coefficients(mod_aic_3)$gdp[-(n*p+1), 1]
gdp.i = 1 # gdp is the first column
gdp.index.min = 2+(gdp.i-1)*(n*p+1) 
gdp.index.max = (n*p+1)*gdp.i
gdp.index = c(gdp.index.min:gdp.index.max)
var.gdp = var.all[gdp.index,gdp.index]

## coefficient and variance-covariance matrix for import
coef.import = coefficients(mod_aic_3)$import[-(n*p+1), 1]
import.i = 2 # import is the second column
import.index.min = 2+(import.i-1)*(n*p+1) 
import.index.max = (n*p+1)*import.i
import.index = c(import.index.min:import.index.max)
var.import = var.all[import.index,import.index]

## coefficient and variance-covariance matrix for export
coef.export = coefficients(mod_aic_3)$export[-(n*p+1), 1]
export.i = 3 # export500 is the third column
export.index.min = 2+(export.i-1)*(n*p+1) 
export.index.max = (n*p+1)*export.i
export.index = c(export.index.min:export.index.max)
var.export = var.all[export.index,export.index]

## coefficient and variance-covariance matrix for unemployment rate
coef.unemployment_rate = coefficients(mod_aic_3)$unemployment_rate[-(n*p+1), 1]
unemployment_rate.i = 4 # unemployment_rate500 is the fourth column
unemployment_rate.index.min = 2+(unemployment_rate.i-1)*(n*p+1) 
unemployment_rate.index.max = (n*p+1)*unemployment_rate.i
unemployment_rate.index = c(unemployment_rate.index.min:unemployment_rate.index.max)
var.unemployment_rate = var.all[import.index,import.index]

## coefficient and variance-covariance matrix for pce
coef.pce = coefficients(mod_aic_3)$pce[-(n*p+1), 1]
pce.i =5 # pce500 is the fifth column
pce.index.min = 2+(pce.i-1)*(n*p+1) 
pce.index.max = (n*p+1)*pce.i
pce.index = c(pce.index.min:pce.index.max)
var.pce = var.all[pce.index,pce.index]

The stepwise model, however, omit the unemployment factor, resulting in a higher significance level for other factors than the VAR model. Overall the VAR model is preferred over the stepwise model.

Question 2c

Evaluate the goodness of fit for the restricted BIC model using the multivariate ARCH test, the Jarque-Bera test and the Portmanteau test. State which assumptions are satisfied, and which are violated. (Note: While we evaluate the residuals for the normality assumption, we do not necessarily assume normality of the data. We use the normality assumption if we use the t-test to evaluate statistical significance.)

# ARCH-LM test: This function computes univariate and multivariate ARCH-LM tests for a VAR(p).
arch.test(rstrcted, lags.single=2, multivariate.only = TRUE)
## 
##  ARCH (multivariate)
## 
## data:  Residuals of VAR object rstrcted
## Chi-squared = 2238.6, df = 1125, p-value < 2.2e-16
# Jarque-Bera Test: This function computes univariate and multivariate Jarque-Bera tests and multivariate skewness and kurtosis tests for the residuals of a VAR(p) or of a VECM in levels.
normality.test(rstrcted, multivariate.only = TRUE)
## $JB
## 
##  JB-Test (multivariate)
## 
## data:  Residuals of VAR object rstrcted
## Chi-squared = 2521.4, df = 10, p-value < 2.2e-16
## 
## 
## $Skewness
## 
##  Skewness only (multivariate)
## 
## data:  Residuals of VAR object rstrcted
## Chi-squared = 127.65, df = 5, p-value < 2.2e-16
## 
## 
## $Kurtosis
## 
##  Kurtosis only (multivariate)
## 
## data:  Residuals of VAR object rstrcted
## Chi-squared = 2393.8, df = 5, p-value < 2.2e-16
# Portmanteau: Compute the BoxPierce or LjungBox test statistic for examining the null hypothesis of independence in a given time series. These are sometimes known as portmanteau tests.
serial.test(rstrcted,lags.pt=2)
## 
##  Portmanteau Test (asymptotic)
## 
## data:  Residuals of VAR object rstrcted
## Chi-squared = 72.92, df = 0, p-value < 2.2e-16

Response

The ARCH test shows that there is autoregressive conditional heteroscedasticity because the p value is extremely small. The normality test shows that the data is not multivariate-normal distributed because the p value is extremely small. And the last Portmanteau test result shows that the errors are serially correlated.
